mbly district|49th]]\n|term_start3 = 2001\n|term_end3 = 2006\n|predecessor3 = [[Gloria J. Romero]]\n|successor3 = [[Mike Eng]]\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1953|7|7}}\n|birth_place = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|residence = [[Monterey Park, California|Monterey Park]], [[California]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|spouse = {{marriage|[[Mike Eng]]|1978}}\n|alma_mater = [[University of California, Los Angeles]] (B.A.)<br>[[California School of Professional Psychology]] ([[doctorate of philosophy|PhD]])\n|profession = [[Politician]]<br>[[Psychologist]]\n}}\n{{Chinese|title=Judy May Chu|t=\u8d99\u7f8e\u5fc3|s=\u8d75\u7f8e\u5fc3|p=Zh\u00e0o M\u011bix\u012bn|w=Chao<sup>4</sup> Mei<sup>3</sup>-hsin<sup>1</sup>|mi={{IPAc-cmn|zh|ao|4|-|m|ei|3|x|in|1}}|y=Jiuh M\u00e9ihs\u0101m|j=Ziu6 Mei5 sam1|gd=Jiu6 M\u00e9i5 sem1|showflag=p}}\n'''Judy May Chu''' ({{zh|t=\u8d99\u7f8e\u5fc3}}, born July 7, 1953)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.familytreelegends.com/records/calbirths?c=search&first=Judy&last=Chu&spelling=Exact&4_year=&4_month=0&4_day=0&5=&7=&SubmitSearch.x=0&SubmitSearch.y=0 |title=California Births, 1905\u20131995 |publisher=Familytreelegends.com |date= |accessdate=2011-10-25}}</ref> is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|CA|27}}, serving in Congress since 2009. She is a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]].\n\nChu was previously Chair of the [[State Board of Equalization (California)|California Board of Equalization]], representing the 4th District.<ref name=\"BOE_about\" /> She had also served on the [[Garvey School District|Garvey Unified School District]] Board of Education, the [[Monterey Park, California|Monterey Park]] City Council (with five terms as mayor) and the [[California State Assembly]].\n\nChu ran in the [[California's 32nd congressional district special election, 2009|32nd congressional district special election]] for the seat that was vacated by [[Hilda Solis]] after she was confirmed as Barack Obama's [[U.S. Secretary of Labor]] in 2009.<ref name=\"lat122308\">{{Cite news| url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/politics/cal/la-me-solis23-2008dec23,0,858937.story | title=Solis' House seat draws interest of prominent politicians | author=Larrubia, Evelyn | publisher=''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' | date=2008-12-23 | accessdate=2008-12-24}}</ref>  She defeated Republican candidate Betty Tom Chu and Libertarian candidate Christopher Agrella in a runoff election on July 14, 2009.<ref name=\"huffingtonpost.com\">Blood, Michael P. [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/huff-wires/20090715/us-socal-calif-special-election-congress/ Democrat captures US House seat in LA county], ''Huffington Post'', 15 July 2009.</ref> She is the first [[Chinese American]] woman ever elected to the [[United States Congress|U.S. Congress]].<ref>Merl, Jean. [http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2009/07/judy-chu-wins-congressional-race.html \"Judy Chu trounces rivals in congressional race\"], ''Los Angeles Times'', 14 July 2009.</ref> Chu was redistricted to the 27th District in 2012, but was still re-elected to a third term, defeating Republican challenger [[Jack Orswell]].\n\n==Early life, education, and academic career==\nJudy Chu is the second of four children of Judson and May Chu, who were married in 1948 in their ancestral home of [[Xinhui District|Xinhui]], [[Jiangmen]], [[Guangdong]]. After getting married, they moved to [[Los Angeles]], near 62nd Street and Normandie Avenue, where Chu was born and grew up until her early teen years, when the family moved to the [[Bay Area]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.singtaousa.com/052109/ss02.php|title=\u8d99\u7f8e\u5fc3\u662f\u5fc3\u7406\u5b78\u535a\u58eb| work=Singtaousa News| year=2008|accessdate=2009-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Judy Chu becomes first Chinese American woman elected to Congress|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-judy-chu16-2009jul16,0,2984735.story|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=July 16, 2009|first=Jean|last=Merl}}</ref>\n\nChu graduated with a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in mathematics from the [[University of California, Los Angeles]].  She then earned a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] in psychology from the [[California School of Professional Psychology]].\n\nShe taught as a psychology professor at the [[Los Angeles Community College District]] for 20 years, including 13 years at [[East Los Angeles College]].<ref name=\"BOE_about\">{{cite web| year=2007 | title=Vice Chair Judy Chu | url=http://www.boe.ca.gov/members/jchu/about_member.html| publisher= California Board of Equalization | accessdate=14 May 2007 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070213024949/http://www.boe.ca.gov/members/jchu/about_member.html |archivedate = 13 February 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"LWV\">{{cite web| first= Judy | last=Chu | year=2002 | title=Political Philosophy for Judy Chu| url=http://www.smartvoter.org/2002/11/05/ca/state/vote/chu_j/philosophy.html| work=SmartVoter.org| publisher=League of Women Voters of California Education Fund | accessdate=14 May 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Local politics==\n[[File:Judy Chu 2007.jpg|thumb|left|Chu in 2007, while still a member of the Board of Equalization]]Chu's first elected position was Board Member for the [[Garvey School District]] in [[Rosemead, California]] in 1985. In 1988 she was elected to the city council of [[Monterey Park, California|Monterey Park]], where she served as mayor for three terms.<ref name=\"BOE_about\" /><ref name=\"LWV\" /> She ran for the [[California State Assembly]] in 1994, but lost the Democrat primary to [[Diane Martinez]]; in 1998, she lost the primary to [[Gloria J. Romero|Gloria Romero]].\n\nChu was elected to the State Assembly in a May 15, 2001, special election after Romero was elected to the [[California State Senate|State Senate]]. She was elected to a full term in 2002 and was reelected in 2004. The district includes [[Alhambra, California|Alhambra]], [[El Monte, California|El Monte]], [[Duarte, California|Duarte]], [[Monterey Park, California|Monterey Park]], [[Rosemead, California|Rosemead]], [[San Gabriel, California|San Gabriel]], [[San Marino, California|San Marino]] and [[South El Monte, California|South El Monte]], within [[Los Angeles County, California|Los Angeles County]].<ref>{{Wayback |date=20060528234302 |url=http://democrats.assembly.ca.gov/members/a49/biography.htm |title=Biography at California Assembly website }}</ref>\n\nBarred by term limits from running for a third full term in 2006, Chu was elected to the State Board of Equalization from the 4th District, representing most of Los Angeles County.\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n;2009\n{{Main|California's 32nd congressional district special election, 2009}}\nChu decided to run for the 2009 special election for the [[California's 32nd congressional district]] after U.S. Congresswoman [[Hilda Solis]] was appointed to become President [[Barack Obama]]'s [[U.S. Secretary of Labor]]. Chu led the field in the May 19 special election. However, due to the crowded nature of the primary (eight Democrats and four Republicans filed) she only got 32% of the vote, well short of the 50% vote needed to win outright.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=503912 |title=CA District 32 \u2013 Special Election Race \u2013 May 19, 2009 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=March 27, 2012}}</ref> In the run-off election, she defeated [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] Betty Chu (her cousin-in-law and a then-Monterey Park City Councilwoman) 62%\u201333%.<ref name=\"huffingtonpost.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=545433 |title=CA District 32 \u2013 Special Election Runoff Race \u2013 Jul 14, 2009 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=March 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\n;2010\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in California, 2010#District 32}}\nShe had been heavily favored due to the district's heavy Democrat tilt and with a [[Cook Partisan Voting Index]] of D+15, it is one of the safest Democratic districts in the nation. She won re-election to her first full term with 71% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=488365 |title=CA \u2013 District 32 Race \u2013 Nov 02, 2010 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=March 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\n;2012\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in California, 2012#District 27}}\nIn August 2011, she decided to run in the newly redrawn [[California's 27th congressional district]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Galindo |first=Erick |url=http://www.pasadenastarnews.com/news/ci_18639765 |title=Judy Chu announces plans to run for new San Gabriel Valley congressional district |publisher=Pasadena Star-News |date=August 8, 2011 |accessdate=March 27, 2012}}</ref> The district has the second highest percentage of [[Asian American]]s in the state with 37%, behind the newly redrawn [[California's 17th congressional district|17th CD]] which is 50% Asian.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spreadsheets.latimes.com/usCongress-2011-0729/?force=True&sortOrder=1&sortColumn=7 |title=Demographics of the new congressional districts \u2013 Spreadsheets |publisher=Los Angeles Times |date=2011-07-29 |accessdate=March 27, 2012}}</ref> Registered Democrats make up 42% of the district. Obama won the district with 63% in the 2008 presidential. [[Jerry Brown]] won with 55% in the 2010 gubernatorial election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://redistrictingpartners.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/Final-2011-Congressional-Spreadsheet.pdf |title=Final 2011 Congressional Spreadsheet |publisher=Redistricting Partners |date= |accessdate=March 27, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://redistrictingpartners.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/Final-2011-Congressional-Spreadsheet-2.pdf |title=Final 2011 Congressional Spreadsheet 2 |publisher=Redistricting Partners |date= |accessdate=March 27, 2012}}</ref> Representative Chu won re-election by defeating Republican [[Jack Orswell]] 64% to 36%.<ref>[[United States House of Representatives elections in California, 2012]]</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nChu was sworn into office on July 16, 2009.\n\n;Abortion\nChu cosponsored the Global Sexual and Reproductive Health Act of 2010 which authorizes the President of the United States to support measures providing abortions and other reproduction assistance to women in developing countries.  In 2010, Chu voting against measures proposed by the U.S. House of Representatives to strip government funding to [[Planned Parenthood]], and opposed restricting federal funding of abortions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Political Positions of Judy Chu|url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=19279508&category=views&id=20100506104232|work=The Political Guide|publisher=The Political Guide|accessdate=4 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Rep. Chu Continues Fighting to Protect the Health and Lives of Women|url=http://chu.house.gov/2011/03/rep-chu-continues-fighting-to-protect-the-health-and-lives-of-women.shtml|work=Congresswoman Judy Chu|publisher=Congresswoman Judy Chu|accessdate=4 September 2011}}</ref>  Chu has received ratings of 100 from all Pro-Choice affiliates including  Planned Parenthood Affiliates of California in 2001, 2002, 2003, 2004, 2005, and 2006.<ref name=\"Issue Rating\">[http://www.votesmart.org/issue_rating_category.php?can_id=16539 Issue Rating] at votesmart.org</ref> She has also received ratings of 100 from the NARAL pro-choice California in 2003, 2004, 2005, and 2006 <ref name=\"Issue Rating\" /> while receiving very low ratings given by Pro-Life organizations in 2003, 2004, 2005, and 2006.<ref name=\"Issue Rating\" />\n\n;Budget\nIn 2009, Chu voted to increase the debt ceiling to $12.394 trillion. In 2010, Chu voted to increase the debt ceiling to $14.294 trillion. In January 2011, she voted against a bill to reduce spending on non-security items to fiscal year 2008 levels.  In 2011, Chu voted against the Budget Control Act of 2011, which incrementally raised the debt ceiling.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Political Positions of Judy Chu|url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=19279508&category=views&id=812045649521|work=The Political Guide|publisher=The Political Guide|accessdate=4 September 2011}}</ref>\n\n;Defense of Civil Liberties\nChu opposed the \"See Something, Say Something Act of 2011,\" which provides \"immunity for reports of suspected terrorist activity or suspicious behavior and response.\" She said, \"if a person contacts law enforcement about something based solely on someone's race, religion, ethnicity, or national origin, they would not receive immunity from civil lawsuits.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Kamboj|first=Kirti|title=H.R. 963: The 'See a Minority, Report a Terrorist' Act of 2011?|url=http://www.hyphenmagazine.com/blog/archive/2011/08/hr-963-see-minority-report-terrorist-act-2011|work=Hyphen Magazine|publisher=Hyphen Magazine|accessdate=4 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Dye|first=Shawn|title=Watch Rep. Judy Chu Argue for Protections against Racial Profiling|url=http://www.unfinishedbusiness.org/20110808-watch-rep-judy-chu-argue-for-protections-against-racial-profiling/|newspaper=Unfinished Business|date=August 8, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn July 24, 2013, the United States House of Representatives voted on Amendment 100 to the H.R. 2397 Department of Defense Appropriations Act of 2014 which if passed would have ended the authority for the blanket collection of records under the Patriot Act.<ref>[http://rules.house.gov/bill/hr-2397 H.R. 2397 - DEPARTMENT OF DEFENSE APPROPRIATIONS ACT, 2014]</ref> Chu voted \"Aye\" to pass amendment 100 and end the blanket collection authority; however, the amendment did not pass with the \"Noes\" blocking the amendment 217-205.<ref>[[FINAL VOTE RESULTS H R 2397 RECORDED VOTE 24-Jul-2013 6:51 PM]]</ref>\n;Internet policy\nIn 2011, Rep. Chu became a co-sponsor of Bill H.R.3261 otherwise known as the [[Stop Online Piracy Act]].<ref name=\"govtrack\">[http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bill.xpd?bill=h112-3261 Bill H.R.3261]; GovTrack.us;</ref>\n\n;Apology for the Chinese Exclusion Act\nOn June 18, 2012, the United States House of Representatives passed a resolution, introduced by Congresswoman Chu, that formally expresses the ''regret'' of the House of Representatives for the [[Chinese Exclusion Act]], which imposed almost total restrictions on Chinese immigration and naturalization and denied Chinese-Americans basic freedoms because of their ethnicity. This was only the fourth time that the U.S. Congress issued an apology to a group of people.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/112/hres683|title=H.Res. 683 (112th)|accessdate=August 9, 2012|author=112th Congress (2012)|date=June 8, 2012 |work=Legislation\n|publisher=GovTrack.us|quote=Expressing the regret of the House of Representatives for the passage of laws that adversely affected the Chinese in the United States, including the Chinese Exclusion Act.\n}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n[[File:RepChuSwearingIn.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Chu and husband Mike Eng, with Nancy Pelosi, at Chu's Swearing In ceremony for the U.S. House of Representatives]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on the Judiciary|Committee on the Judiciary]]'''\n**[[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on Crime, Terrorism, and Homeland Security|Subcommittee on Crime, Terrorism, and Homeland Security]]\n**[[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on Intellectual Property, Competition, and the Internet|Subcommittee on Intellectual Property, Competition, and the Internet]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Small Business|Committee on Small Business]]'''\n**[[United States House Small Business Subcommittee on Contracting and Workforce|Subcommittee on Contracting and Workforce]]\n**[[United States House Small Business Subcommittee on Economic Growth, Tax and Capital Access|Subcommittee on Economic Growth, Tax and Capital Access]]\n**[[United States House Small Business Subcommittee on Agriculture, Energy and Trade|Subcommittee on Agriculture, Energy and Trade]]\n<ref name=\"Issue Rating\"/>\n\n===Caucuses===\n*[[American Sikh Congressional Caucus]] (Co-Chair)\n*[[Congressional Progressive Caucus]] (Vice-Chair)\n*[[Congressional Asian Pacific American Caucus]] (Chair)\n\n==Personal life==\nChu married [[Mike Eng]] in 1978. (Eng took Chu's seat on the Monterey Park City Council in 2001, when Chu left the council after getting elected to the [[California State Assembly|Assembly]], and in 2006 he took Chu's seat on the Assembly, when Chu left the Assembly.)\n\nChu's nephew, [[Lance Corporal Harry Lew]], a [[United States Marine Corps|US Marine]], committed suicide while serving in [[Afghanistan]] on April 3, 2011, allegedly as a result of [[hazing]] from fellow Marines after Lew repeatedly fell asleep during his watch. Chu described her nephew as a patriotic American and said that those responsible must be brought to justice.<ref>McAvoy, Audrey. [http://news.yahoo.com/3-marines-trial-alleged-hazing-011434225.html 3 Marines will go to trial for alleged hazing], ''Associated Press'', 26 October 2011.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Asian Americans|Greater Los Angeles|Biography|Politics}}\n{{Commons category|Judy Chu}}\n*[http://chu.house.gov/ Congresswoman Judy Chu] official U.S. House site\n*[http://www.judychu.org/ Judy Chu for Congress]\n*{{Ballotpedia|Judy_Chu|Judy Chu}}\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/California/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Judy_Chu_%5BD-27%5D|Judy Chu}}\n{{CongLinks | congbio = C001080 | ballot = Judy_Chu | nndb = 519/000208892 | votesmart = 16539 | govtrack = 412379 | opencong = 412379 | rollcall = 30544 | politifact = | fec = H0CA32101 | opensecrets = N00030